Synchronous programming refers to code execution where each line is executed one after another in a sequential manner, waiting for the completion of the previous line before moving on to the next. In contrast, asynchronous programming allows for multiple lines or tasks to be executed concurrently without waiting for the completion of previous operations.

In JavaScript, the traditional way of handling code execution is synchronously. Here's an example of synchronous programming in JavaScript:

```javascript
function getData(url) {
  return fetch(url).then(response => response.json());
}

const data = getData('https://example.com/data');
console.log(data); // The console log will wait until the fetch promise is resolved before executing.
```
In this example, the JavaScript code will block and wait for the `fetch` function to return a response before moving on to the next line, which is logging the data.

Asynchronous programming, on the other hand, allows your code to continue execution without waiting for a resource or operation to complete. It uses callbacks, promises, or async/await to handle asynchronous operations. Here's an example of asynchronous programming in JavaScript:

```javascript
async function getData(url) {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  const data = await response.json();
  console.log(data); // This will log the data after the fetch promise is resolved.
}

getData('https://example.com/data');
```
In this example, we've made the `getData()` function asynchronous using the `async` keyword. The `await` keyword allows us to pause the execution of the asynchronous function until the Promise returned by `fetch` is resolved. As a result, our code doesn't block and can move on to the next line (console log) before fetching is complete.

In summary, synchronous programming executes code sequentially while waiting for each operation to finish, whereas asynchronous programming allows multiple operations to be executed concurrently without blocking the main execution thread.

